---
import RoomLayout from '../../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';

const currentDraftHref = '/drafts/who-steals-from-children-latest.docx';

const sections = [
  {
    label: 'Opening record',
    title: 'Editor\'s Preface and State of the Fight',
    description:
      'The reason for keeping an annual public record, the current shape of the field, and the difference between a trust promise on paper and a trust someone is watching.',
  },
  {
    label: 'State portraits',
    title: 'Oregon, Nevada, South Dakota, and Mississippi',
    description:
      'Four current working portraits showing different faces of the same fiduciary problem: seizure, drift, recovery, and enforceable trustee duties.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Dispatches',
    title: 'Where the fight is moving now',
    description:
      'Short present-tense reports from litigation, legislation, public records, agency practice, and local advocates as the school-trust field comes back into view.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Credits',
    title: 'Who stepped up',
    description:
      'A place to name the people who held records, made claims visible, corrected the Library, or carried a state fight far enough for others to see.',
  },
];
---

<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="Who Steals from Children"
  subtitle="The 2026 working edition of the annual record of the fight for America's school trust lands."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="writing-wsfc-2026-edition"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
      Writing Room . 2026 working edition
    </p>

    <p class="byline text-slate-700">
      <strong>Edited by David Sullivan</strong>
    </p>

    <p class="spine mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-800">
      This book keeps the present-tense record: where school trusts are being
      diverted, where they are being defended, where old law is being recovered,
      and where people have stepped forward to make the beneficiary claim
      visible again.
    </p>

    <section class="current-draft mt-8" aria-labelledby="current-draft-heading">
      <p class="current-draft-kicker">Current draft</p>
      <h2 id="current-draft-heading">2026 working edition</h2>
      <p>
        The current public draft is the June 8, 2026 review build. It is the
        national annual survey edition of <em>Who Steals from Children</em>,
        not the older Oregon-only Volume 1 page that previously occupied this
        address. The Oregon origin story is now carried separately by
        <a href="/writing/books/accidental-plaintiff/"><em>The Accidental Plaintiff</em></a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={currentDraftHref} class="download-link">Download the current Word draft -&gt;</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-10" aria-labelledby="what-this-is-heading">
      <h2 id="what-this-is-heading">What this book does</h2>
      <p>
        School-trust failures are easy to miss when each state is treated as a
        local anomaly. The point of this annual record is to make the pattern
        legible. Each edition gathers state portraits, live disputes, recovery
        examples, and contributor records in one place so trustees, lawyers,
        parents, librarians, and advocates can see the national field rather
        than a set of scattered local fights.
      </p>
      <p>
        The working edition remains open to correction. Claims are meant to be
        checked against primary records; unresolved items stay visible until
        they are verified or withdrawn.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>

  <section class="contents mt-10" aria-labelledby="contents-heading">
    <h2 id="contents-heading">What's inside</h2>
    <div class="contents-grid">
      {sections.map((section) => (
        <article>
          <p>{section.label}</p>
          <h3>{section.title}</h3>
          <span>{section.description}</span>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="series-invite mt-10" aria-labelledby="series-invite-heading">
    <h2 id="series-invite-heading">A record people can add to</h2>
    <p>
      The Library is looking for documented school-trust fights from every
      state: agency records, court papers, board minutes, local histories,
      trustee reports, and first-person accounts from people who lived the
      fight. A trust survives only when somebody is watching, and the record
      gets stronger when the witnesses bring the paper.
    </p>
    <p>
      Write to the <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a> with a state,
      a document, or a correction.
    </p>
  </section>

  <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-slate-600">
    <a href="/writing/">Back to the Writing Room</a>
  </p>
</RoomLayout>

<style>
  .byline {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .spine {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    padding: 0.25rem 0 0.25rem 1rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }
  .current-draft {
    padding: 1rem 1.15rem;
    border: 1px solid #d8c18b;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #fff8df;
    color: #422006;
  }
  .current-draft-kicker,
  .contents-grid article p {
    display: block;
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-family: var(--font-sans, system-ui, sans-serif);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.09em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #64748b;
  }
  .current-draft h2,
  .contents h2,
  .series-invite h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
  }
  .current-draft h2 {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
  }
  .download-link {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .contents h2,
  .series-invite h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .contents-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.85rem;
  }
  .contents-grid article {
    border: 1px solid #d7dce4;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #fff;
    padding: 1rem;
  }
  .contents-grid h3 {
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-size: 1.02rem;
    color: #0f172a;
  }
  .contents-grid span,
  .series-invite p {
    color: #334155;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
